Today, however, John is here
to talk about his latest book,

00:00:28.320 --> 00:00:30.300
"The Whole Foods Diet,"
but it's about how

00:00:30.300 --> 00:00:34.290
a plant-based lifestyle can help
us live longer and live well.

00:00:34.290 --> 00:00:38.684
So can we have a big round
of applause for John Mackey.

00:00:38.684 --> 00:00:41.486
[APPLAUSE]

00:00:45.042 --> 00:00:46.750
JOHN MACKEY: I'm
excited about this book.

00:00:46.750 --> 00:00:49.090
I'm very proud of it.

00:00:49.090 --> 00:00:54.000
This kind of sums up my 39 years
of healthy living experiments

00:00:54.000 --> 00:00:56.580
and kind of what I've learned.

00:00:56.580 --> 00:00:57.615
I wrote it with--

00:00:57.615 --> 00:01:00.360
how many of you saw the
film "Forks Over Knives?"

00:01:00.360 --> 00:01:02.190
Anybody see those films?

00:01:02.190 --> 00:01:05.129
And the two doctors that
were the two young doctors

00:01:05.129 --> 00:01:08.520
in the film, Alona Pulde
and Matt Ledderman,

00:01:08.520 --> 00:01:09.870
they work for Whole Foods.

00:01:09.870 --> 00:01:12.420
And so they are my
co-authors in the book,

00:01:12.420 --> 00:01:15.030
because I'm a
grocer, not a doctor.

00:01:15.030 --> 00:01:17.910
So good when somebody asks me
those tough medical questions

00:01:17.910 --> 00:01:20.010
to say, I'm not a
doctor, but this

00:01:20.010 --> 00:01:22.320
is what Matt and Alona say.

00:01:22.320 --> 00:01:27.300
So this presentation I'm about
to make, I've got to tell you,

00:01:27.300 --> 00:01:29.250
I'm looking at a
very young audience.

00:01:29.250 --> 00:01:32.010
You're all bulletproof still.

00:01:32.010 --> 00:01:36.385
But it's kind of
depressing, the statistics

00:01:36.385 --> 00:01:37.420
I'm going to put forth.

00:01:37.420 --> 00:01:40.260
Also, I'm looking at a
very young but also looks

00:01:40.260 --> 00:01:44.880
like a very healthy and
health-conscious audience.

00:01:44.880 --> 00:01:48.360
So some of this will--

00:01:48.360 --> 00:01:50.940
well, the numbers are
true, even if they don't

00:01:50.940 --> 00:01:53.560
apply to you or your friends.

00:01:53.560 --> 00:01:57.360
So we are an incredibly
unhealthy nation.

00:01:57.360 --> 00:01:59.740
And most people don't realize
how unhealthy America is.

00:01:59.740 --> 00:02:03.870
But by most world
health indicators,

00:02:03.870 --> 00:02:06.660
we do not score very highly.

00:02:06.660 --> 00:02:11.880
And you can see here that what's
the leading causes of death

00:02:11.880 --> 00:02:15.589
in the United States,
heart disease is still

00:02:15.589 --> 00:02:16.380
the leading killer.

00:02:16.380 --> 00:02:18.330
Cancer has just about caught it.

00:02:18.330 --> 00:02:22.646
But if you add stroke into
the cardiovascular category,

00:02:22.646 --> 00:02:24.270
along with heart
disease, heart disease

00:02:24.270 --> 00:02:25.800
is still very far ahead.

00:02:25.800 --> 00:02:27.780
Interestingly
enough, medical care

00:02:27.780 --> 00:02:31.410
itself is the third leading
cause of death in our country.

00:02:31.410 --> 00:02:35.760
And then the diseases that would
kill us about 100 years ago

00:02:35.760 --> 00:02:40.350
in the early 1900s were
the infectious diseases.

00:02:40.350 --> 00:02:42.810
And those have largely
been wiped out.

00:02:42.810 --> 00:02:45.790
They're not the same kind
of killers they were.

00:02:45.790 --> 00:02:49.310
If you went back
100 years ago, they

00:02:49.310 --> 00:02:53.676
were dying from tuberculosis,
and they were dying from--

00:02:53.676 --> 00:02:55.050
they didn't have
any antibiotics.

00:02:55.050 --> 00:02:57.900
So they'd get infections, and
they did get blood poisoning

00:02:57.900 --> 00:02:59.170
and die off.

00:02:59.170 --> 00:03:02.500
So our problem now is that
the things that are killing us

00:03:02.500 --> 00:03:05.340
are life-style diseases--
dietary lifestyle diseases

00:03:05.340 --> 00:03:06.630
primarily.

00:03:06.630 --> 00:03:09.450
And medical care being the
third leading cause of death

00:03:09.450 --> 00:03:12.180
is not something that
doctors want to tell people.

00:03:12.180 --> 00:03:16.500
But adverse drug
effects, far more people

00:03:16.500 --> 00:03:18.960
die from prescription
drugs in America

00:03:18.960 --> 00:03:23.300
than die from illegal drugs
by many factors every year.

00:03:23.300 --> 00:03:25.770
And primarily because
of the interactions

00:03:25.770 --> 00:03:28.740
of these different drugs
that people are taking,

00:03:28.740 --> 00:03:30.960
combined with the type
of infections people

00:03:30.960 --> 00:03:32.730
get when they go into hospitals.

00:03:32.730 --> 00:03:35.170
So those two together
are the lion share.

00:03:35.170 --> 00:03:37.410
And plus just stupid
mistakes that hospitals make.

00:03:37.410 --> 00:03:42.082
That's the third leading cause
of death for medical care.

00:03:42.082 --> 00:03:43.290
Here are the grim statistics.

00:03:43.290 --> 00:03:45.947
We're now up to
71% of all adults

00:03:45.947 --> 00:03:47.280
in this country are overweight--

00:03:47.280 --> 00:03:49.860
71%.

00:03:49.860 --> 00:03:54.210
And 38% of adults are now obese.

00:03:54.210 --> 00:03:57.420
The thing is, the trend lines
are still not leveled off.

00:03:57.420 --> 00:04:00.150
They are continuing
to steadily climb.

00:04:00.150 --> 00:04:03.750
And obesity is now
estimated to cost our nation

00:04:03.750 --> 00:04:06.990
about $190 billion a year.

00:04:06.990 --> 00:04:11.880
So it's gone from 15% obesity
in the US back in 1971

00:04:11.880 --> 00:04:15.960
to now it's about 38%, the
statistic I gave before.

00:04:15.960 --> 00:04:20.070
So it's more than doubled
in the last 40 years.

00:04:20.070 --> 00:04:22.950
And it's not just a problem
in the United States,

00:04:22.950 --> 00:04:24.330
it's a problem across the world.

00:04:24.330 --> 00:04:28.110
Again, this does not look like
it did before I turned it over

00:04:28.110 --> 00:04:29.745
here.

00:04:29.745 --> 00:04:32.610
But you can see
the blue represents

00:04:32.610 --> 00:04:37.740
where these countries were
in obesity back in 1980.

00:04:37.740 --> 00:04:40.644
And you can see what's
happened since 2008.

00:04:40.644 --> 00:04:42.060
And this is
primarily, we've begun

00:04:42.060 --> 00:04:44.700
to export our dietary
patterns of eating

00:04:44.700 --> 00:04:47.290
that we do in the United
States across the world.

00:04:47.290 --> 00:04:50.716
And the result is a
crisis in obesity.

00:04:50.716 --> 00:04:52.590
And the United States
is the fattest country,

00:04:52.590 --> 00:04:56.730
but you will see that the
UK, Mexico, and South Africa

00:04:56.730 --> 00:04:58.007
are close behind.

00:04:58.007 --> 00:05:00.090
And the trend lines show
that Mexico will probably

00:05:00.090 --> 00:05:01.506
pass up the United
States sometime

00:05:01.506 --> 00:05:03.900
in the next decade or so
for the fattest country

00:05:03.900 --> 00:05:08.010
in the world, a dubious honor.

00:05:08.010 --> 00:05:09.690
This is probably
the most disturbing

00:05:09.690 --> 00:05:11.700
is what's happened to children.

00:05:11.700 --> 00:05:15.930
17% of the children alive today
between the ages of 2 and 19

00:05:15.930 --> 00:05:17.880
are now already obese--

00:05:17.880 --> 00:05:19.810
not just overweight,
they're obese.

00:05:19.810 --> 00:05:22.950
And 70% of children
under 12 years of age

00:05:22.950 --> 00:05:27.230
already show signs of
heart disease at age 12.

00:05:27.230 --> 00:05:33.360
And already 19% are showing
dietary related chronic disease

00:05:33.360 --> 00:05:35.560
conditions.

00:05:35.560 --> 00:05:37.295
How has it happened?

00:05:37.295 --> 00:05:38.420
Oh, I know what's happened.

00:05:40.950 --> 00:05:42.130
We've eaten more.

00:05:42.130 --> 00:05:43.130
We have more calories.

00:05:43.130 --> 00:05:45.530
And this is the truth
that's not spoken.

00:05:45.530 --> 00:05:49.310
We eat, per capita,
25% more calories

00:05:49.310 --> 00:05:51.600
than we did 40 years ago.

00:05:51.600 --> 00:05:54.960
So we're eating more
calorie-dense foods.

00:05:54.960 --> 00:05:56.360
And that's why we're fatter.

00:05:56.360 --> 00:05:58.340
It's not rocket science.

00:05:58.340 --> 00:06:01.160
We are simply eating the
wrong kinds of foods,

00:06:01.160 --> 00:06:04.860
and we're eating a
lot more calories.

00:06:04.860 --> 00:06:08.130
So if you look at the
different food groups

00:06:08.130 --> 00:06:10.730
where we've increased,
so sugar is usually

00:06:10.730 --> 00:06:12.757
held out as a scapegoat,
and I am certainly

00:06:12.757 --> 00:06:13.840
not going to defend sugar.

00:06:13.840 --> 00:06:16.040
Sugar is not a healthy food.

00:06:16.040 --> 00:06:17.123
But it's usually held out.

00:06:17.123 --> 00:06:20.420
You have books, the Gary Taubes
and all the low-carb people

00:06:20.420 --> 00:06:24.920
are making sugar into
the villain nutrient.

00:06:24.920 --> 00:06:27.980
And sugar did increase per
capita in the last 40 years.

00:06:27.980 --> 00:06:33.170
It went up about 10% from
where it was 40 years ago

00:06:33.170 --> 00:06:34.250
on a per capita basis.

00:06:34.250 --> 00:06:35.390
So sugar has increased.

00:06:35.390 --> 00:06:39.470
But by far, by far,
the biggest increases

00:06:39.470 --> 00:06:43.830
have been in three
major categories.

00:06:43.830 --> 00:06:45.680
The first one, oils--

00:06:45.680 --> 00:06:46.960
vegetable oils.

00:06:46.960 --> 00:06:50.120
We're now eating
about 67% more oil

00:06:50.120 --> 00:06:53.460
that we ate 40 years ago
on a per capita basis.

00:06:53.460 --> 00:06:59.220
And I blame the
Mediterranean diet

00:06:59.220 --> 00:07:03.300
for that, because people became
convinced that olive oil was

00:07:03.300 --> 00:07:04.650
a health food.

00:07:04.650 --> 00:07:06.870
And if you look at the
history of the Mediterranean

00:07:06.870 --> 00:07:09.210
diet in the
Mediterranean countries,

00:07:09.210 --> 00:07:11.680
what they were doing when
they did the research,

00:07:11.680 --> 00:07:14.085
they discovered that, yes,
the Mediterranean people down

00:07:14.085 --> 00:07:19.500
in Crete and Sardinia and some
of the Mediterranean countries

00:07:19.500 --> 00:07:21.539
that had these great
health outcomes,

00:07:21.539 --> 00:07:23.330
they studied their
diet, and they found out

00:07:23.330 --> 00:07:25.340
they're eating a lot more
fruits and vegetables.

00:07:25.340 --> 00:07:27.230
They were eating less meat.

00:07:27.230 --> 00:07:28.790
They were eating more beans.

00:07:28.790 --> 00:07:29.870
They were eating lots.

00:07:29.870 --> 00:07:31.060
They had their own gardens.

00:07:31.060 --> 00:07:33.600
They were eating lots
more whole grains.

00:07:33.600 --> 00:07:35.160
And they ate a little more fish.

00:07:35.160 --> 00:07:36.900
They didn't eat so much meat.

00:07:36.900 --> 00:07:40.440
And they used olive
oil instead of butter,

00:07:40.440 --> 00:07:43.240
and they drank red wine.

00:07:43.240 --> 00:07:45.120
But what was the takeaway
that Americans got

00:07:45.120 --> 00:07:46.728
about the Mediterranean diet?

00:07:46.728 --> 00:07:47.664
AUDIENCE: Olive oil.

00:07:47.664 --> 00:07:48.600
AUDIENCE: Red wine.

00:07:48.600 --> 00:07:49.750
JOHN MACKEY: Exactly.

00:07:49.750 --> 00:07:51.740
Olive oil and red wine.

00:07:51.740 --> 00:07:54.030
And arguably, the
people were healthy,

00:07:54.030 --> 00:07:58.580
not because of those two foods,
but in spite of them, meaning

00:07:58.580 --> 00:08:02.130
it was the fresh fruits and
vegetables and whole grains

00:08:02.130 --> 00:08:04.500
and beans and
fewer animal foods.

00:08:04.500 --> 00:08:06.570
Not to mention, people
in Crete were walking

00:08:06.570 --> 00:08:09.890
like nine miles every day.

00:08:09.890 --> 00:08:13.540
And so we drew the wrong
conclusions from it.

00:08:13.540 --> 00:08:16.890
So oil was a huge cause
of the weight gain.

00:08:16.890 --> 00:08:23.480
Also refined flours, the
number of donuts and bagels

00:08:23.480 --> 00:08:27.420
and croissants and just
kind of white bread

00:08:27.420 --> 00:08:31.680
that has been consumed has gone
way up in the last 40 years.

00:08:31.680 --> 00:08:37.870
And the final thing is dairy
fats, particularly cheese.

00:08:37.870 --> 00:08:41.340
In 1915, the per capita
consumption of cheese

00:08:41.340 --> 00:08:44.730
was three pounds a
person a year in the US.

00:08:44.730 --> 00:08:49.830
Today, 100 years later, it's
34 and 1/2 pounds of cheese.

00:08:54.040 --> 00:08:57.570
Well, that's 1,000%-- more
than 1,000% increase--

00:08:57.570 --> 00:08:58.940
10x.

00:08:58.940 --> 00:09:02.700
And I don't eat
any cheese at all.

00:09:02.700 --> 00:09:07.050
So somebody is probably eating
about 69 pounds of cheese

00:09:07.050 --> 00:09:09.270
to make up the difference.

00:09:09.270 --> 00:09:12.840
And you probably
know who you are.

00:09:12.840 --> 00:09:14.380
So here's the thing.

00:09:14.380 --> 00:09:16.230
Let's put this in a
big great context.

00:09:16.230 --> 00:09:18.450
Let's put it in
evolutionary context.

00:09:18.450 --> 00:09:21.750
Being fat was not a
problem that human beings

00:09:21.750 --> 00:09:23.760
have had for most of our
evolutionary history.

00:09:23.760 --> 00:09:25.360
Quite the opposite.

00:09:25.360 --> 00:09:27.870
We were just trying to get
enough calories to stay alive.

00:09:27.870 --> 00:09:29.240
It was about survival.

00:09:29.240 --> 00:09:32.700
When we were
gatherers and hunters,

00:09:32.700 --> 00:09:35.580
there wasn't very much
calorie-dense food available.

00:09:35.580 --> 00:09:38.010
People were foraging for
fruits and vegetables,

00:09:38.010 --> 00:09:40.950
and maybe they can get
some starchy tubers.

00:09:40.950 --> 00:09:43.080
This was before
we had agriculture

00:09:43.080 --> 00:09:46.230
that through hybridization
and selective breeding

00:09:46.230 --> 00:09:50.360
we could increase the
sweetness of food,

00:09:50.360 --> 00:09:52.860
increase the
carbohydrates that might

00:09:52.860 --> 00:09:55.740
be in a root vegetable
like a sweet potato

00:09:55.740 --> 00:09:59.940
or a squash or a potato.

00:09:59.940 --> 00:10:04.290
And so we just were
putting massive quantities

00:10:04.290 --> 00:10:07.530
of food, very high
fiber content,

00:10:07.530 --> 00:10:08.820
just to get enough calories.

00:10:08.820 --> 00:10:12.450
And when they could pull down
a wild animal, wild game--

00:10:12.450 --> 00:10:15.780
then they'd get a rich source
of concentrated protein

00:10:15.780 --> 00:10:19.140
and calories, although
nothing like the kind of meat

00:10:19.140 --> 00:10:21.540
that people eat today,
where you have corn-fed beef

00:10:21.540 --> 00:10:26.200
and we've basically fattened
up our livestock animals.

00:10:26.200 --> 00:10:32.970
So what this translates into
is our evolutionary program,

00:10:32.970 --> 00:10:37.830
our evolutionary predisposition
to crave calorie-dense foods.

00:10:37.830 --> 00:10:40.600
We like things that have
a lot of calories in them.

00:10:40.600 --> 00:10:41.940
We like sugar.

00:10:41.940 --> 00:10:43.350
We like fat.

00:10:43.350 --> 00:10:45.480
We like white rice.

00:10:45.480 --> 00:10:48.900
We like ice cream,
particularly like things

00:10:48.900 --> 00:10:52.691
that combine sugar and fat,
like a nice dark chocolate candy

00:10:52.691 --> 00:10:53.190
bar.

00:10:53.190 --> 00:10:53.689
Yum.

00:10:56.400 --> 00:10:56.970
We like oil.

00:10:56.970 --> 00:10:59.460
Oil is the most calorie-dense
food you can eat.

00:10:59.460 --> 00:11:02.430
One tablespoon of
oil has 120 calories.

00:11:02.430 --> 00:11:06.300
So now that we've
become more affluent,

00:11:06.300 --> 00:11:10.590
we can get calorie-dense
foods, not on a feast day,

00:11:10.590 --> 00:11:11.430
not on a rare event.

00:11:11.430 --> 00:11:15.360
We can have it three
times a day or more.

00:11:15.360 --> 00:11:16.890
And so we do.

00:11:16.890 --> 00:11:19.890
And as the rest of the
world becomes more affluent,

00:11:19.890 --> 00:11:23.520
that same craving for calorie
density stays in play.

00:11:23.520 --> 00:11:25.579
And so that's why the
whole world is getting fat,

00:11:25.579 --> 00:11:27.120
because we can eat
more animal foods.

00:11:27.120 --> 00:11:28.203
We can eat more ice cream.

00:11:28.203 --> 00:11:29.520
We can eat more oil.

00:11:29.520 --> 00:11:31.710
We can eat more
sugar, and we are.

00:11:31.710 --> 00:11:34.290
And we're basically
killing ourselves

00:11:34.290 --> 00:11:37.140
with our craving for
calorie-dense foods.

00:11:37.140 --> 00:11:39.842
And so that translates
into the thing

00:11:39.842 --> 00:11:41.550
most people aren't
really conscious of is

00:11:41.550 --> 00:11:42.840
food addictions.

00:11:42.840 --> 00:11:45.570
Food addictions are a
really serious problem.

00:11:45.570 --> 00:11:50.850
And most people are addicts,
but they don't know it

00:11:50.850 --> 00:11:52.950
until they try to quit.

00:11:52.950 --> 00:11:55.780
And then when you try
to change your diet,

00:11:55.780 --> 00:11:57.640
you find that it's
quite difficult.

00:11:57.640 --> 00:12:00.280
You can change it for
a while, but then you

00:12:00.280 --> 00:12:02.470
tend to drift back
to the old pattern

00:12:02.470 --> 00:12:03.590
because it's deeply set.

00:12:07.450 --> 00:12:11.710
Type 2 diabetes is
almost towards pandemic,

00:12:11.710 --> 00:12:13.880
because we're now
about 12% of people

00:12:13.880 --> 00:12:21.580
are identified as diabetic, but
we have 35% of the population,

00:12:21.580 --> 00:12:23.350
an estimated 86
million people are

00:12:23.350 --> 00:12:27.700
already pre-diabetic and on
their way to being diabetic.

00:12:27.700 --> 00:12:29.380
So we're talking about--

00:12:29.380 --> 00:12:32.140
gosh, I mean, almost half
of the adult population

00:12:32.140 --> 00:12:34.610
is either diabetic
or pre-diabetic.

00:12:34.610 --> 00:12:38.931
And the complications of
diabetes down the road

00:12:38.931 --> 00:12:39.930
are absolutely horrible.

00:12:39.930 --> 00:12:42.190
Look at what happens to people.

00:12:42.190 --> 00:12:43.310
They can go blind.

00:12:43.310 --> 00:12:45.250
They have to
amputate their feet.

00:12:45.250 --> 00:12:47.170
They get hearing loss.

00:12:47.170 --> 00:12:48.920
They can get osteoporosis.

00:12:48.920 --> 00:12:50.170
They get Alzheimer's.

00:12:50.170 --> 00:12:51.190
It's a horrible disease.

00:12:55.780 --> 00:12:58.046
Type 2 diabetes is totally
a lifestyle disease.

00:12:58.046 --> 00:13:00.670
I'm going to talk about how you
can reverse that disease fairly

00:13:00.670 --> 00:13:03.660
quickly by dietary changes.

00:13:03.660 --> 00:13:04.504
Heart disease.

00:13:04.504 --> 00:13:05.920
A million and a
half people a year

00:13:05.920 --> 00:13:08.120
die from a heart
attack or stroke.

