00:26:25.690 --> 00:26:28.460
except for a small subset of the
Seventh Day Adventists in Loma

00:26:28.460 --> 00:26:30.470
Linda, none of them are vegans.

00:26:30.470 --> 00:26:35.330
But they all eat real
foods, real whole foods,

00:26:35.330 --> 00:26:40.487
about 90% plant
based, no exceptions.

00:26:40.487 --> 00:26:42.570
Here's the Okinawans are
particularly interesting.

00:26:42.570 --> 00:26:47.240
The Okinawa elder diet,
so 70% of their calories

00:26:47.240 --> 00:26:52.940
came from sweet potatoes,
12% from rice, and 7%

00:26:52.940 --> 00:26:56.420
from grains they were
eating, and then 6% from soy.

00:26:56.420 --> 00:26:59.540
So they were eating
approximately 85%

00:26:59.540 --> 00:27:02.390
of their calories were coming
from complex carbohydrates

00:27:02.390 --> 00:27:03.410
or starches.

00:27:03.410 --> 00:27:04.340
Astounding.

00:27:04.340 --> 00:27:06.570
Almost 85%.

00:27:06.570 --> 00:27:08.130
And you can see
they weren't vegan.

00:27:08.130 --> 00:27:11.390
They got some pork,
about 1% from pork.

00:27:11.390 --> 00:27:14.740
1% from eggs, 1% from
dairy, and 1% for fish.

00:27:14.740 --> 00:27:18.920
So they were a 96%
vegan diet and almost no

00:27:18.920 --> 00:27:21.120
processed foods whatsoever.

00:27:21.120 --> 00:27:26.370
And very little oil, only
2% of the calories from oil.

00:27:26.370 --> 00:27:28.895
The Seventh Day Adventists,
again, the Seventh Day

00:27:28.895 --> 00:27:34.210
Adventists are a religious group
that is very focused on health.

00:27:34.210 --> 00:27:36.870
Their interpretation
of the Bible

00:27:36.870 --> 00:27:40.560
is that God wants us
to eat extremely mostly

00:27:40.560 --> 00:27:43.977
plant-based diets and wants
us to be very healthy.

00:27:43.977 --> 00:27:46.560
So what's so interesting about
that, these people don't smoke,

00:27:46.560 --> 00:27:48.870
they don't drink.

00:27:48.870 --> 00:27:51.690
Their parts, they have people
of faith, they have religion,

00:27:51.690 --> 00:27:53.620
they have community.

00:27:53.620 --> 00:27:57.060
And so they're perfect
to do a study on diet,

00:27:57.060 --> 00:27:58.680
because that's where they vary.

00:27:58.680 --> 00:28:00.150
So they had the--

00:28:00.150 --> 00:28:01.890
you can see from
body mass index,

00:28:01.890 --> 00:28:03.664
the vegans had the
lowest body mass index,

00:28:03.664 --> 00:28:05.580
followed by the vegetarians,
and the omnivores

00:28:05.580 --> 00:28:09.990
were much higher-- the
omnivores at 28.8%.

00:28:09.990 --> 00:28:12.930
30.0 gets you to obesity levels.

00:28:12.930 --> 00:28:15.380
Anything above 24 is overweight.

00:28:15.380 --> 00:28:20.160
So only the vegans were actually
kind of at an ideal weight.

00:28:20.160 --> 00:28:24.440
But the vegan Adventist who
ate nuts and seeds, exercised

00:28:24.440 --> 00:28:27.810
and not smoked, they are the
longest-lived cohort we've ever

00:28:27.810 --> 00:28:30.370
discovered in modern times.

00:28:30.370 --> 00:28:33.420
And the men, on average,
lived 14 years longer

00:28:33.420 --> 00:28:35.190
than the average
Caucasian American,

00:28:35.190 --> 00:28:36.940
and the females lived
10 years longer.

00:28:36.940 --> 00:28:38.190
And look at those risk rates--

00:28:38.190 --> 00:28:41.010
60% lower risk of
cancer, 76% lower risk

00:28:41.010 --> 00:28:44.940
of heart disease,
and even women 98%

00:28:44.940 --> 00:28:47.700
lower rates of heart disease
in the Adventist communities

00:28:47.700 --> 00:28:48.750
that were the vegans.

00:28:48.750 --> 00:28:51.000
Some phenomenal statistics.

00:28:51.000 --> 00:28:55.620
And I think one of my friends,
the Dr. Garth Davis said,

00:28:55.620 --> 00:28:59.040
if everyone ate like an
Adventist, everyone would

00:28:59.040 --> 00:29:02.440
have the same health outcomes.

00:29:02.440 --> 00:29:05.250
So Dean Ornish.

00:29:05.250 --> 00:29:10.500
Dean Ornish proved the
cure for heart disease,

00:29:10.500 --> 00:29:13.440
because he did a
study, and it was

00:29:13.440 --> 00:29:16.900
eating a vegetarian diet,
very low in fat, very high

00:29:16.900 --> 00:29:18.140
in starches--

00:29:18.140 --> 00:29:21.240
70% to 75% from starches.

00:29:21.240 --> 00:29:23.580
And the outcomes
were extraordinary.

00:29:23.580 --> 00:29:25.450
He was able to
reverse heart disease.

00:29:25.450 --> 00:29:28.130
So here's a guy who
reversed heart disease,

00:29:28.130 --> 00:29:32.450
who cured heart disease
and nobody cares.

00:29:32.450 --> 00:29:35.450
The whole heart industry
is all about cracking

00:29:35.450 --> 00:29:40.620
people's chest open and going in
and doing angioplasty or doing

00:29:40.620 --> 00:29:43.440
stents, doing some kind
of heroic technological

00:29:43.440 --> 00:29:46.410
intervention, when
they never needed

00:29:46.410 --> 00:29:49.720
to have that kind of surgery,
that through diet, they

00:29:49.720 --> 00:29:51.910
completely reversed
their heart disease.

00:29:51.910 --> 00:29:54.340
And yet nobody cares.

00:29:54.340 --> 00:29:55.904
Nobody seems to know about it.

00:29:55.904 --> 00:29:58.320
That's been followed up by the
incredible work of Caldwell

00:29:58.320 --> 00:30:02.490
Esselstyn, who did his own
work where he had people--

00:30:02.490 --> 00:30:05.910
it was a much smaller cohort
than Ornish worked with,

00:30:05.910 --> 00:30:08.490
but here's a diet,
a very pure diet--

00:30:08.490 --> 00:30:09.660
100% plant-based.

00:30:09.660 --> 00:30:12.240
No oils, no sugars, no
refined carbohydrates, and it

00:30:12.240 --> 00:30:14.940
was a starch-based
diet, very low in fat.

00:30:14.940 --> 00:30:17.380
And the statistics
are phenomenal.

00:30:17.380 --> 00:30:19.440
These are people that
already had advanced

00:30:19.440 --> 00:30:21.280
cardiovascular disease.

00:30:21.280 --> 00:30:25.720
So 89% of his patients actually
adhered to the diet and 11% who

00:30:25.720 --> 00:30:26.670
didn't.

00:30:26.670 --> 00:30:30.810
Those who adhered to it,
only 0.6%, one person,

00:30:30.810 --> 00:30:33.909
experienced a coronary
event in the three years

00:30:33.909 --> 00:30:34.700
that followed this.

00:30:34.700 --> 00:30:37.290
These were people that mostly
had already had heart attacks.

00:30:37.290 --> 00:30:40.500
And 11% of the patients
were non-adherent.

00:30:40.500 --> 00:30:44.490
62% of them have some type of
coronary event in those three

00:30:44.490 --> 00:30:45.990
years.

00:30:45.990 --> 00:30:48.930
Phenomenal success.

00:30:48.930 --> 00:30:51.090
Nutrient density.

00:30:51.090 --> 00:30:53.760
Nutrient density.

00:30:53.760 --> 00:30:56.700
Our society is obsessed
with the macronutrients.

00:30:56.700 --> 00:30:58.862
How much protein
should people eat?

00:30:58.862 --> 00:31:00.570
How many carbohydrates
should people eat?

00:31:00.570 --> 00:31:01.920
And how much fat
should they eat?

00:31:01.920 --> 00:31:02.503
Which is good?

00:31:02.503 --> 00:31:05.990
Carbs are bad, proteins good.

00:31:05.990 --> 00:31:09.270
Fat we used to think was bad,
and now people think it's good.

00:31:09.270 --> 00:31:12.720
And that's what most of these
dietary debates are around.

00:31:12.720 --> 00:31:15.690
And they're kind
of stupid debates,

00:31:15.690 --> 00:31:19.470
because if you're eating
whole foods, mostly plants,

00:31:19.470 --> 00:31:22.270
you're going to get the
right mix of macronutrients.

00:31:22.270 --> 00:31:24.290
What's usually left
out of the discussion

00:31:24.290 --> 00:31:26.670
are the micronutrients,
and these are obviously

00:31:26.670 --> 00:31:29.880
the most important nutrients
from the longevity and health

00:31:29.880 --> 00:31:31.200
standpoint.

00:31:31.200 --> 00:31:34.440
And so that's the
vitamins and minerals

00:31:34.440 --> 00:31:37.860
and the phytochemicals,
the phytonutrients.

00:31:37.860 --> 00:31:42.030
There's estimated that there's
over 10,000 phytonutrients

00:31:42.030 --> 00:31:46.380
that we've now discovered
that have healthful effects

00:31:46.380 --> 00:31:47.790
on our bodies.

00:31:47.790 --> 00:31:50.110
And the foods that are the
most nutrient-dense foods--

00:31:50.110 --> 00:31:51.970
I hope this one came out.

00:31:51.970 --> 00:31:55.517
Based on a nutrient
density per calorie--

00:31:55.517 --> 00:31:56.850
I don't know, can you read that?

00:31:56.850 --> 00:31:59.070
Probably can't, but
at the very bottom,

00:31:59.070 --> 00:32:00.860
the least nutrient-dense
foods you can eat

00:32:00.860 --> 00:32:03.240
are oil and refined
sugars, followed

00:32:03.240 --> 00:32:05.760
by refined grains
and then cheese

00:32:05.760 --> 00:32:08.970
and then full-fat dairy,
then red meat, then eggs.

00:32:08.970 --> 00:32:10.770
We'll move up to all
the different meat

00:32:10.770 --> 00:32:13.350
products, with fish having
the most micronutrient density

00:32:13.350 --> 00:32:14.700
per calorie.

00:32:14.700 --> 00:32:17.520
And then the most nutrient-dense
foods you can eat,

00:32:17.520 --> 00:32:21.780
not surprisingly, are
vegetables, particularly--

00:32:21.780 --> 00:32:23.570
particularly-- leafy greens.

00:32:23.570 --> 00:32:27.990
Those are the superfoods,
things like kale and watercress

00:32:27.990 --> 00:32:33.020
and collards, mustard
greens, these type of foods,

00:32:33.020 --> 00:32:33.690
and spinach.

00:32:33.690 --> 00:32:36.660
These are like super
nutritionally dense foods

00:32:36.660 --> 00:32:37.640
on a per-calorie basis.

00:32:37.640 --> 00:32:39.480
And all the vegetables
and the fruits,

00:32:39.480 --> 00:32:43.930
the beans, the whole
grains, nuts and seeds.

00:32:43.930 --> 00:32:50.870
So what Dr. Joel Fuhrman
argues is that in his system,

00:32:50.870 --> 00:32:54.640
the key to health is to maximize
your micronutrient density

00:32:54.640 --> 00:32:56.320
per calorie consumed.

00:32:56.320 --> 00:33:00.130
Health is equal
to macronutrients

00:33:00.130 --> 00:33:01.600
divided by calories.

00:33:01.600 --> 00:33:03.310
So he's arguing
that we should be

00:33:03.310 --> 00:33:07.210
eating an intensely
micronutrient-dense diet, which

00:33:07.210 --> 00:33:11.050
means lots of fruits
and vegetables.

00:33:11.050 --> 00:33:14.350
Let's talk a bit
about low-carb diets.

00:33:14.350 --> 00:33:19.570
I call the low-carb diets
the zombies of the food,

00:33:19.570 --> 00:33:22.090
because they never die.

00:33:22.090 --> 00:33:24.160
You kill them, and
then another generation

00:33:24.160 --> 00:33:27.250
comes along and embraces it.

00:33:27.250 --> 00:33:29.320
So these have all
been best sellers.

00:33:29.320 --> 00:33:31.370
The Atkins program,
the South Beach diet,

00:33:31.370 --> 00:33:34.720
which is the best-selling diet
book of all time, The Zone.

00:33:34.720 --> 00:33:37.240
Mark Hyman now is
popularizing the stuff.

00:33:37.240 --> 00:33:40.030
The paleo and the Primal diets.

00:33:40.030 --> 00:33:42.620
You can lose weight
on these diets

00:33:42.620 --> 00:33:48.400
if you are also being conscious
of your portion control.

00:33:48.400 --> 00:33:53.560
And there's one great saving
grace of the low-carb diets.

00:33:53.560 --> 00:33:56.410
You stop eating the
highly processed grains.

00:33:56.410 --> 00:33:57.922
You stop eating the sugar.

00:33:57.922 --> 00:33:59.380
And by the way, if
you just cut out

00:33:59.380 --> 00:34:01.290
sugar and highly
processed grains,

00:34:01.290 --> 00:34:04.070
I guarantee you you're
going to feel better.

00:34:04.070 --> 00:34:06.640
The problem is that we
haven't evolved that way.

00:34:06.640 --> 00:34:08.650
We've evolved as plant eaters.

00:34:08.650 --> 00:34:09.969
If you look at our nearest--

00:34:09.969 --> 00:34:12.670
not only did we evolve that
was in our paleolithic times,

00:34:12.670 --> 00:34:16.030
but if we go back even
evolutionary further back

00:34:16.030 --> 00:34:20.889
to our closest primate
cousins, the gorillas, who

00:34:20.889 --> 00:34:23.889
are 100% plant-based, we
share about 98% of the DNA.

00:34:23.889 --> 00:34:28.300
And the chimps and the
bonobos, we're closer to 99%.

00:34:28.300 --> 00:34:30.400
The gorilla is a
100% plant based,

00:34:30.400 --> 00:34:33.909
and the bonobos and the chimps
are about 95% plant based.

00:34:33.909 --> 00:34:35.830
And they're eating
high quantities

00:34:35.830 --> 00:34:38.745
of nutrient-dense
foliage, lots of greens.

00:34:38.745 --> 00:34:39.620
That's what they eat.

00:34:39.620 --> 00:34:45.520
They eat tons of greens, tons
of fruits and tons of veggies.

00:34:45.520 --> 00:34:47.739
So plant eaters, if
you're going to be a plant

00:34:47.739 --> 00:34:50.100
eater, necessarily going
to be a high-carb eater,

00:34:50.100 --> 00:34:52.000
because carbohydrates,
that's where they are.

00:34:52.000 --> 00:34:53.560
Carbs are in the plants.

00:34:53.560 --> 00:34:55.510
They're not in the animal foods.

00:34:55.510 --> 00:34:58.390
So when we talk about a low-carb
diet, let's translate that.

00:34:58.390 --> 00:35:01.780
Low-carb diet means a low-plant
diet and a high-animal foods

00:35:01.780 --> 00:35:02.920
diet.

00:35:02.920 --> 00:35:05.830
And eating high
quantities of animal foods

00:35:05.830 --> 00:35:07.870
correlates very closely--

00:35:07.870 --> 00:35:11.320
it's been shown in study after
study after study after study--

00:35:11.320 --> 00:35:14.675
that it correlates very closely
with heart disease, stroke,

00:35:14.675 --> 00:35:15.175
and cancer.

00:35:18.090 --> 00:35:19.990
And all the low-carb
diets could inherently

00:35:19.990 --> 00:35:26.300
be very high in calories and
very low in nutrient density.

00:35:26.300 --> 00:35:29.050
So it's good to minimize
all the simple sugars,

00:35:29.050 --> 00:35:31.060
but then they throw
out the healthy carbs,

00:35:31.060 --> 00:35:32.470
the healthy starches.

00:35:32.470 --> 00:35:38.290
And starch foods such as yams,
whole grains, winter squashes,

00:35:38.290 --> 00:35:41.050
they are super-healthy
foods for us.

00:35:41.050 --> 00:35:44.470
All historical civilizations,
as I've already argued,

00:35:44.470 --> 00:35:48.450
base their diet primarily
on eating starch foods.

00:35:48.450 --> 00:35:50.090
Paleo.

